NFL Play Prediction Modeling¶

The NFL is an extremely competitive league where every play has incredibly high stakes. In a league where there are only 16 regular season games and teams average about 70 offensive plays per game, every play is incredibly important. This means that information on your opponent is key. The greatest players are able to disect the opposing team and know exactly what they are about to do. Greats like Peyton Manning and Luke Kuechly have ridden this ability to the top of their respective positions and make their teams better for it.

This means that any additional information you can get about what your opponent is about to do will make your team that much more deadly. So in this notebook, I'll be building a model that uses information about the game state to predict whether the offense will be running or passing the ball on their next play.

To do this, I've scraped play data from Pro Football Reference. This data contains information like Down, Distance, and time left in the game in addition to what type of play was ran. I've limited it effort to plays ran in the 2014 - 2018 seasons and only plays on 1st-3rd down.

First we need to load our dependencies and data.

def plot_confusion_matrix(cm, classes,
                          normalize=False,
                          title='Confusion matrix',
                          cmap=plt.cm.Blues):
    """
    This function prints and plots the confusion matrix.
    Normalization can be applied by setting `normalize=True`.
    """
    if normalize:
        cm = cm.astype('float') / cm.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis]
        print("Normalized confusion matrix")
    else:
        print('Confusion matrix, without normalization')

    #print(cm)

    plt.imshow(cm, interpolation='nearest', cmap=cmap)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.colorbar()
    tick_marks = np.arange(len(classes))
    plt.xticks(tick_marks, classes, rotation=45)
    plt.yticks(tick_marks, classes)

    fmt = '.2f' if normalize else 'd'
    thresh = cm.max() / 2.
    for i, j in itertools.product(range(cm.shape[0]), range(cm.shape[1])):
        plt.text(j, i, format(cm[i, j], fmt),
                 horizontalalignment="center",
                 color="white" if cm[i, j] > thresh else "black")

    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
    plt.tight_layout()

Data Munging¶

The first thing we need to do is perform some alterations and calculations to get the model inputs I want.

There is an issue in the data where if a play results in a touchdown, the score is already updated. We want the pre-touchdown score. So if the word "Touchdown" is in the Detail column, we will subtract 6 from the offensive score

Now we need to calculate field position. To keep things positive, we will use the distance to touchdown. Thus the further down the field an offense is the lower that value will be.

The last calculation I want is the amount of time left in the game. Our data currently contains quarter and minute information so we will need to do some conversions.

In [3]:
plays['Location_team_abbrev'] = plays.Location.str.slice(start = 0 , stop = 3)
plays['Yard_line'] = plays.Location.str.slice(start = -2 ).astype(int)
plays['year'] = pd.DatetimeIndex(plays.Date).year

# Capture offensive and defensive scores in separate columns
scores = plays['Score'].str.split('-', expand = True)
plays['Off_score'] = scores[0].astype(int)
plays['Def_score'] = scores[1].astype(int)

# Edit offensive score to account for score prior to touchdowns
plays['Off_score'] = pd.np.where(plays.Detail.str.lower().str.contains("touchdown"), plays.Off_score -6, plays.Off_score)

# Calculate score differential
plays['Score_diff'] = plays.Off_score - plays.Def_score

# Calculate Distance to Goal line
team_abbrv_dict = plays[['Tm', 'Location_team_abbrev']].groupby(['Tm', 'Location_team_abbrev']).size().reset_index().sort_values(by = 0, ascending = False)[:32][['Tm', 'Location_team_abbrev']]
team_abbrv_dict.columns = ['Tm', 'Off_team_abbrev']

plays = plays.merge(team_abbrv_dict, on = 'Tm')
plays['Distance_to_goal'] = pd.np.where(plays.Yard_line == 50, 50,
           pd.np.where(plays.Location_team_abbrev == plays.Off_team_abbrev, (50 - plays.Yard_line) + 50, plays.Yard_line))

# Calculate time left in game
times = plays.Time.str.split(':', expand = True)
plays['Time_dec'] = times[0].astype(float) + (times[1].astype(float)/60)
plays['Time_left_in_game'] = pd.np.where(plays.Quarter == 1, 45 + plays['Time_dec'],
           pd.np.where(plays.Quarter == 2, 30 + plays['Time_dec'],
                      pd.np.where(plays.Quarter == 3, 15 + plays['Time_dec'], plays['Time_dec'])))

# HomeAway captures neutral site games as N.  For this effort I'll calculate neutral site games as away games
plays['HomeAway'] = pd.np.where(plays.HomeAway == 'N', 'R', plays.HomeAway)
# I'll also binarize HomeAway
plays['HomeGame'] = pd.np.where(plays.HomeAway == 'H', 1, 0)

Target analysis¶

The playlocation column tells us what type and where the play was ran. It will eventually be our target. Lets make it a little more readable and store in a new variable.

sns.countplot(plays.Play_Location_Desc)
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')
plt.show()

Looks like, more often than not, a team is going to either throw it short, or run it up the middle. A run anywhere but up the middle has roughly the same liklihood as one another but teams only rarely throw it deep. Pro Football Reference defines a deep pass attempt as any pass with 15 or more attempted air yards. For simpliciy sake, in this effort, I will only be classifying between a run or a pass attempt. In later iterations I may take this further and attempt to predict a more specific play type.

When broken down to simply run vs pass, the attempts are almost identical. This means that a blind guess would result in being right about 50% of the time.

If we break down run vs. pass plays by down, 1st down is weighted slightly to Rushing, 2nd Down is split pretty evenly, and 3rd down is weighted heavily to Passing

Since teams want to score if possible they are much more careful about letting time run off the clock which results in the play density going up. Seeing increased rushes early in the game goes along with the idea of "establishing the run" early in the game.

Modelling¶

Now we can begin creating models, I'll start off with a logistic regression as a baseline. These models are easy to interpret and easy to make so they make a great starting point. Unfortunately they tend to not be very accurate.

Logistic Regression¶

In [10]:
modcolumns = ['Down', 'ToGo', 'HomeGame', 'Score_diff', 'Distance_to_goal', 'Time_left_in_game']
X = plays[modcolumns]
y = pd.np.where(plays.play == 'Pass', 1, 0)

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = .33, random_state = 51)

# Logistic Regression requires scaled inputs so we will use sklearns StandardScaler to do the lifting for us
ss = StandardScaler()
X_train_scaled = ss.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_scaled = ss.transform(X_test)
X_train_scaled = pd.DataFrame(X_train_scaled, columns = X.columns)
X_test_scaled = pd.DataFrame(X_test_scaled, columns = X.columns)

logreg = LogisticRegression()
logreg.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)
train_preds = logreg.predict(X_train_scaled)
train_acc = accuracy_score(y_train, train_preds)
y_pred = logreg.predict(X_test_scaled)
test_acc = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
print(f'In-Sample Accuracy: {train_acc} Test Accuracy: {test_acc}')

This is all great but can we make this model a little more accurate? Well I suspect there are non-linear relationships in this data so lets try a decision tree.

Decision Tree¶

Decision trees are excellent at picking up on the subtle interactions between variables and are very easy to read so they are always an interesting model type.

In [12]:

y_pred = tree.predict(X_test)
test_acc = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
print(f'Accuracy: {round(test_acc * 100 , 2)}%')

Accuracy: 68.44%

So now we see an increased accuracy up to 68%! Lets plot the first couple splits of this tree.

So the most first split is created off of whether a play is coming on 1st/2nd down or on 3rd down. Makes sense!

Decision Trees are great but there are even better tree based algorithms. Lets see if we can get an increase from either a Random Forest Ensemble model or an XGBoost tree model.

Random Forest¶

Random forests are simply an extension of decision trees where multiple trees are created and each tree is fit on a bootstrapped sample of the training data. The results of each tree are then combined into one final score which is the output of this model type. These model types are not as easy to read as decision trees though since there are many trees to look through.

Decision trees begin having hyperparameters that we will need to tune in order to get the best results. I will do only minimal tuning here; focusing on the n_estimators and max_depth parameters.

First a quick tune of n_estimators.

In [14]:
rcParams['figure.figsize'] = 8,5
n_estimators = [1, 2, 4, 8, 16, 32, 64]
train_results = []
test_results = []
for estimator in n_estimators:
   rf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=estimator, n_jobs=-1)
   rf.fit(X_train, y_train)
   train_pred = rf.predict(X_train)
   false_positive_rate, true_positive_rate, thresholds = roc_curve(y_train, train_pred)
   roc_auc = auc(false_positive_rate, true_positive_rate)
   train_results.append(roc_auc)
   y_pred = rf.predict(X_test)
   false_positive_rate, true_positive_rate, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, y_pred)
   roc_auc = auc(false_positive_rate, true_positive_rate)
   test_results.append(roc_auc)
sns.lineplot(n_estimators, train_results, label = 'Train AUC')
sns.lineplot(n_estimators, test_results, label = 'Test AUC')
plt.ylabel('AUC score')
plt.xlabel('n_estimators')
plt.title('AUC Score by Number of Trees')
plt.show()

The large difference in training and testing scores is something to keep in mind going forward since it indicates this model as is is overfit. We can help reduce the Variance by adjusting other hyper parameters. This does show us that a 32 estimators should be sufficient for this task however.

Next we will attempt to address the high variance by adjusting the max depth. This controls how many levels are allowed in each tree. By default, no max depth is set and trees are built until each node is pure. This often leads to the overfitting as seen above.

In [15]:
max_depths = range(1, 17)
train_results = []
test_results = []
for max_depth in max_depths:
   rf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=32, max_depth=max_depth, n_jobs=-1)
   rf.fit(X_train, y_train)
   train_pred = rf.predict(X_train)
   false_positive_rate, true_positive_rate, thresholds = roc_curve(y_train, train_pred)
   roc_auc = auc(false_positive_rate, true_positive_rate)
   train_results.append(roc_auc)
   y_pred = rf.predict(X_test)
   false_positive_rate, true_positive_rate, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, y_pred)
   roc_auc = auc(false_positive_rate, true_positive_rate)
   test_results.append(roc_auc)
from matplotlib.legend_handler import HandlerLine2D
sns.lineplot(max_depths, train_results, label = 'Train AUC')
sns.lineplot(max_depths, test_results, label = 'Test AUC')
plt.ylabel('AUC score')
plt.xlabel('Max Depth')
plt.title('Train and Test Scores vs Max Depth')
plt.show()

As we can see, allowing for a max depth approaching 16, we start to see a divergence in the training and testing results. This divergence starts to become apparent after about 12 so moving forward we will use a max depth of 11.

That's as much parameter tuning as I want to do here though it is often advisable to tune the criterion and min_samples_split parameters as well. For now lets create our final random forest model using 32 estimators and a max depth of 11 and see what that gets us.

In [16]:
rfc = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=32, max_depth=11)
rfc.fit(X_train, y_train)
train_preds = rfc.predict(X_train)
train_acc = accuracy_score(y_train, train_preds)
y_pred = rfc.predict(X_test)
test_acc = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
print(f'Accuracy: {round(test_acc * 100,2)}%')

Accuracy: 68.98%

So with these parameters, we see an accuracy of 69.12% which is slightly better than the decision tree from before. So for now this is our champion model. Predicting the correct play type 69% of the time is great but for our final model, lets turn to the big boy in the tree based classifier genre, the XGBoost algorithm.

Extreme Gradient Boosted Trees¶

Extreme Gradient Boosted Tree (XGBoost) algorithms are an extension of gradient boosted machines which fit sequential decision trees on the residuals of all previous trees. These algorithms can be quite complex and require more extensive parameter tuning but are state of the art when it comes to creating accurate predictions. For a gentle introduction to XGBoost algorithms, see this article.

So lets begin training our XGBoost algorithm.

In this effort, we will want to train a number of parameters, starting similarly to the random forest model with n_estimators. XGBoost allows for early stopping however which will help us train this parameter.

In [17]:
# fit model to training data using Early Stopping
xgb = XGBClassifier(n_estimators=5000)
eval_set = [(X_train, y_train), (X_test, y_test)]
xgb.fit(X_train, y_train, eval_metric=["logloss", "auc"], eval_set=eval_set, verbose=False, early_stopping_rounds = 15)

# make predictions for test data
y_pred = xgb.predict(X_test)
predictions = [round(value) for value in y_pred]

# evaluate predictions
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, predictions)
print("Accuracy: %.2f%%" % (accuracy * 100.0))

# retrieve performance metrics
results = xgb.evals_result()
epochs = len(results['validation_0']['auc'])
x_axis = range(0, epochs)

# plot log loss
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.plot(x_axis, results['validation_0']['logloss'], label='Train')
ax.plot(x_axis, results['validation_1']['logloss'], label='Test')
ax.legend()
plt.ylabel('Log Loss')
plt.title('XGBoost Log Loss')
plt.show()

# plot AUC
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.plot(x_axis, results['validation_0']['auc'], label='Train')
ax.plot(x_axis, results['validation_1']['auc'], label='Test')
ax.legend()
plt.ylabel('AUC Score')
plt.title('AUC Score vs. Number of Estimators')
plt.show()

Accuracy: 69.33%

Now that we know we want to use 305 estimators, we will want to tune max_depth and min_child_weight first as those will result in the largest increase in score. To do this, we will use sklearn's GridSearchCV function. Additionaly, since we are using cross validation, we can use the entire dataset instead of splitting into train and test.

So now we have an alpha of .7 and lambda of 4. We could continue training these values but we will leave them there.

The last thing we want to do is to reduce the learning rate and use early stopping to find our final parameters. The default learning rate is 0.3, so we will lower it to 0.1.

We can use a small loop to find the optimum learning rate.

In [27]:
learning_rates = [0.0001, 0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 0.2, 0.3]

for learning_rate in learning_rates:
    # fit model to training data using Early Stopping
    xgb = XGBClassifier(max_depth = 4, 
                        min_child_weight = 4, 
                        gamma = .35,
                        subsample = .8,
                        colsample_bytree = .85,
                        reg_alpha = .7, 
                        reg_lambda = 4,
                        learning_rate = learning_rate,
                        n_estimators=5000,
                        n_jobs = 16)
    eval_set = [(X_train, y_train), (X_test, y_test)]
    xgb.fit(X_train, y_train, eval_metric=["logloss", "auc"], eval_set=eval_set, 
            verbose=False, early_stopping_rounds = 50)

    # make predictions for test data
    y_pred = xgb.predict(X_test)
    predictions = [round(value) for value in y_pred]

    # evaluate predictions
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, predictions)
    print(f"Learning Rate: {learning_rate} Estimators: {xgb.best_ntree_limit} Accuracy: {accuracy * 100.0}%\n " )

Conclusions¶

So after everything is said and done, we have created an XGBoost model to predict whether a team will be running or passing on their next play that is correct 70% of the time! While I'm satisfied with this model for now, I believe that adding in additional information to the model such as offensive and defensive rankings, weather, and potentially even previous play success rates could result in an even greater model. We could also attempt some deep learning models to see if that helps but that is beyond the scope of what I want to do here.

Thank you for following along on this model creation and let me know if you'd like to see more like this.
